dataset.display: Age Adjusted Rate Less Than 20 Yrs Old
dataset.measure: Age Adjusted Rate Less Than 20 Yrs Old
dataset.how_calculated: Average annual number of resident children, less than 20 years old, diagnosed with cancer over the 5 year period, divided by the corresponding age-specific intercensal population estimates (from NYS DOH). The resulting age-specific rates are multiplied by the proportion of the US Census 2000 standard population in each age group. Age-adjusted rate is the sum of these weighted rates; expressed as cases per 1,000,000 children.

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.

info.info_measure: Age Adjusted Rate Less Than 20 Yrs Old
info.info_how_calculated: Average annual number of resident children, less than 20 years old, diagnosed with cancer over the 5 year period, divided by the corresponding age-specific intercensal population estimates (from NYS DOH). The resulting age-specific rates are multiplied by the proportion of the US Census 2000 standard population in each age group. Age-adjusted rate is the sum of these weighted rates; expressed as cases per 1,000,000 children.

Neighborhoods are ranked according to the percent of people whose annual income falls below 100% of the federal poverty level. Rankings are then divided into 3 approximately equal groupings of low, medium and high poverty.
